  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Letter to Venerable Hoewchan, the Head Seat
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I bow deeply before you, Venerable Master of the Chief Seat.

    I am soon to depart for the provincial government at Wansan. Before I go, I must surely visit to pay my respects and receive from your hands a cup of that great spiritual draught. Only then shall I take my leave.

    Regarding your earlier request that I look after the elder Shinju upon my return—this matter is already etched upon my heart. I pray you will worry no further. As for my preparations for travel, though I have had to ask others for assistance, it resembles nothing so much as when the Buddha's followers gladly aid one another according to their means. The day of my departure is already fixed.

    Yet while I dwelt in the capital, each time I visited your dwelling, was I not gladdened by our gentle discourse, by sharing these intimate sentiments? But now that I have taken office, I am bound fast by administrative duties. When melancholy overtakes me, to whom shall I turn for conversation? Only after three years hence may we meet again and speak.

    Meanwhile, I beg you—for the sake of the dharma, tend well to yourself. There is much more I would say, but I must end here.

    I bow twice in reverence.
  footnotes:
    - The 'great spiritual draught' (大道漿) is a poetic reference to Buddhist teaching and wisdom, conveyed through the metaphor of a restorative drink.
    - Lee Gyubo served as an official during the Goryeo period; this letter marks his departure from the capital to take up a provincial post.
    - The 'three years' reflects the typical duration of an official posting in medieval Korean administrative service.
